        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We set 3 basebands on this Science Goal for H2O 325 GHz, HDO 335 GHz, and H2O2 335 GHz. 
For H2O, we need ~1 MHz resolution to spectrally resolve the line shapes in the Martian atmosphere (having a line width of ~20 MHz). In order to obtain the continuum level of the H2O spectra, we use 1.8 GHz-bandwidth configuration. 

For HDO and H2O2, which spectral line is weaker and narrower compared to H2O, we require a higher spectral resolution (~488 kHz and 242 kHz for HDO and H2O2 respectively). Although HDO and H2O2 lines themselves could be as narrow as ~10 MHz (largely depending on how much HDO or H2O2 exists) we set 937 and 240 MHz-bandwidth in order to constain well the continuum level of both lines. 
 </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>During the ALMA-Cycle3 period, the northern summer season corresponds to the period between January/2016 and March/2016. During the period, the diameter of Mars ranges between ~6 and ~11 arcsec. 
In order to achieve our science goals, northern polar cap, and the hot spot of subsurface-atmosphere interaction of water should be resolved. For that, the spatial resolution of the synthesis beam, i.e., angular resolution should be less than 0.6".
 
* About the largest angular scale: 
Our interested HDO/H2O inhomogeneity over the Martian disk has much smaller patchy spatial scales compared to the Martian disk size. We would define the largest angular scale of our proposal as North/South hemispheric structure (i.e. half of the Martian diameter), which is smaller than the largest angular scale of 12-m array (~8 arcsec): i.e., we do not require ACA for our proposal. 
It is true that the continuum emission (which have full disk-spread spatial structure) can suffer the resolve-out problem depending on the date of observation. However, we can recover such missed information by using the apriori knowledge on the Martian disk size (for detail, please see Butler and Bastian (1999), Synthesis Imaging in Radio Astronomy II). In our requested time constraint, Martian diameter increases only up to 11 arcsec. This size is well recoverable only with 12-m array.    
In addition, the use of ACA is not favorable from the scientific point of view. 
The possible time gap between the 12-m array and ACA operations can introduce complicating problems in data analysis (sometimes, impossibility of combining 12-m array and ACA data) due to temporal variability of Martian atmosphere. 
For technical reason, we put 8.2 arcsec as the largest angular scale (theta_LAS) on this OT, which avoids the usage of ACA.  
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In order to fulfill the science goals, the precision of HDO/H2O measurement should be 0.5 wrt VSMOW (i.e., 5-10% of the expected mean HDO/H2O ratio at the Martian atmosphere). 
Here, the most stringent sensitivity requirement comes from the H2O measurements since the terrestrial H2O lines significantly reduce the transmittance at the 325 GHz spectral ranges. Our sensitivity study by radiative transfer model shows that depth of Martian H2O line with typical water vapor abundance at low-latitude is ~ 20 K (see Fig. 5 of Science case document). In order to achieve 0.5 wrt VSMOW accuracy, we should measure the H2O line depth with SNR of 10-15 which is the desired sensitivity ~0.52 K with a spectral bandwidth of 1 MHz.
This 1-MHz bandwidth is required to spectrally resolve the line shape of Martian H2O and HDO lines which fwhm linewidth is about ~20 MHz (see Fig. 5 and Fig. 6 of Science case document). 

* About Spectral Dynamic Range: 
The Martian lines are overlapped on the bright continuum emission of ~200 - 210 K. 
To obtain a good dynamic range in the image synthesis, we will subtract the uniform-disk model visibility from the measurement before inverting the visibility data to dirty image. This procedure has been well applied for Solar system object observations of past interfermeters, and we have successful experiences for that. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>One of our science targets is the HDO/H2O ratio during sublimation at the local summer season. During the ALMA-Cycle3 period, the northern summer season corresponds to the period between January/2016 and March/2016 (3 month in total). 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_TIME_CONSTRAINT</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
