    <prp:abstract>  Mars exploration missions have provided the evidence that Mars once had a large amount of liquid water. However, essential issues are still open questions - How much did Mars have water? Where has a large amount of water gone? To understand the water history, isotopic ratio HDO/H2O is a powerful tracer because it is fractionated owing to atmospheric escape. Since the northern polar cap is considered as major reservoir at the current Mars, HDO/H2O ratio observation during sublimation of polar cap at the local summer is the most essential to estimate the water amount at the early Mars. Although ground-based observations in the near-infrared spectral range have investigated the ratio, they have a certain uncertainty due to (1) insufficient spectral resolution, and (2) effect of dust and water ice. ALMA can demonstrate more accurate observation, that is (1) the narrow Martian H2O and HDO lines can be fully resolved, and (2) effect of the aerosols is negligible. The high resolution HDO/H2O map by ALMA allows us to (1) estimate the amount of the water at the early Mars preciously, and (2) to identify the hot spot of subsurface-atmosphere interaction that would have low HDO/H2O ratio.</prp:abstract>
